{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.0.5"}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Configuration\n\n##### This section configures the document with libraries needed for the workbook activities","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## import required libraries  \nlibrary(tidyverse)\nlibrary(dplyr)\nlibrary(tidyr)\nlibrary(readr)\nlibrary(lubridate)\nlibrary(ggplot2)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2021-08-23T16:55:42.606934Z","iopub.execute_input":"2021-08-23T16:55:42.63395Z","iopub.status.idle":"2021-08-23T16:55:42.653712Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Preparing The Data\n##### In this section raw data is imported and modified and concatenated to make one data set ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## Import raw data  \nbikes_q1_raw <- read_csv(\"Divvy_Trips_2018_Q1.csv\")\nbikes_q2_raw <- read_csv(\"Divvy_Trips_2018_Q2.csv\")\nbikes_q3_raw <- read_csv(\"Divvy_Trips_2018_Q3.csv\")\nbikes_q4_raw <- read_csv(\"Divvy_Trips_2018_Q4.csv\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2021-08-23T16:55:46.675051Z","iopub.execute_input":"2021-08-23T16:55:46.677112Z","iopub.status.idle":"2021-08-23T16:55:46.696925Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## Inspect raw data un-comment to view individual data \n#head(bikes_q1_raw)\n#head(bikes_q2_raw)\n#head(bikes_q3_raw)\n#head(bikes_q4_raw)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### In the section above the data for each quarter has been imported and can now be prepared for analysis.\n##### The information  contained in the columns of the data frames have discrepancies in the column names but consistent formatting elsewhere.\n##### In the next section we rectify the discrepancies in naming of columns ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## standardize column names for all columns across data frame, bikes_q1_raw has different tiles but same structure in columns so columns are renamed to align with other data frames\n\ncolnames(bikes_q1_raw) <- colnames(bikes_q2_raw)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The different data frames can now be concatenated with bind_rows() function into one dataframe object making cleaning, processing and manipulating data more efficient.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## Concatenate all data into a new data frame all_data_df and preview\n\nall_data_df <- bikes_q1_raw %>%\n  bind_rows(bikes_q2_raw,bikes_q3_raw,bikes_q4_raw)\nhead(all_data_df,100)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Process The Data\n##### Cyclistic has several elements of data that was collected and can be used in analysis, the data must be prepared so it is suitable for this task","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## Modify table to include columns ride_length and day_of_week \n\nall_data_df <- all_data_df %>%\n  mutate(ride_length = difftime(end_time,start_time,units=\"secs\"))","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The code above added two new columns to the data frame which should support with the analysis stage","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## remove any duplicate trip records \nall_data_df <- all_data_df %>%\n  distinct(trip_id,.keep_all=TRUE)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The code above is a check to remove any duplicate data to ensure analysis is valid and no errors result for duplication of data. The titles of columns will be adapted to ensure they are descriptive enough. The code below formats the dataframe in accordance with this ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#reformat all_data_df\nall_data_df <- all_data_df %>%\n  rename(ride_id = trip_id\n                   ,rideable_type = bikeid \n                   ,started_at = start_time  \n                   ,ended_at = end_time  \n                   ,start_station_name = from_station_name \n                   ,start_station_id = from_station_id \n                   ,end_station_name = to_station_name \n                   ,end_station_id = to_station_id \n                   ,member_casual = usertype)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The data has over tip data for over 3 million trips and 621 of the 692 stations in the cyclistic network and has a been stored in a dataframe with standard formatting, the final step before analysis is to clean the data\n\n### Cleaning The Data\n##### This section looks at the data and removes any features that may cause errors in analysis and formats the data in a way that supports analysis.The available data will be split and consolidated into new groups to support drill down potential of the analysis.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#consolidate customer group names \nall_data_df <-  all_data_df %>% \n  mutate(member_casual = recode(member_casual\n                           ,\"Subscriber\" = \"member\"\n                           ,\"Customer\" = \"casual\"))","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The code above removes ambiguity of the classification of the customer classes","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#check names \ncheck_groupings <- unique(all_data_df$member_casual)\ncheck_groupings","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The code above allows the user to check if the changes to the data frame have been made if the code shows member and casual as outputs.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# add date,day,month and year columns to data frame to allow grouping in analysis\n\n## create date column from started_at col\nall_data_df <- all_data_df %>%\n  mutate(date = as.Date(all_data_df$started_at))\n\n## create columns for day, month and year and fix data type for ride time (in seconds)\nall_data_df <- all_data_df %>%\n  mutate(month = format(as.Date(all_data_df$date),\"%m\"),day = format(as.Date(all_data_df$date),\"%d\"),year = format(as.Date(all_data_df$date),\"%Y\"),ride_length = as.numeric(as.character(all_data_df$ride_length)),day_of_week = format(as.Date(all_data_df$date), \"%A\"))","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The code above allowed us to create a data frame with date objects that we can now use to group by in our analysis.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## check data produced \nstr(all_data_df)\n## remove gender, birthyear and gender\nall_data_df <- all_data_df %>%\n  select(-birthyear,-gender,-gender)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### Finally we can remove any data that may cause problems in analysis such as negative journey times and quality assurance check-out of bikes.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## Remove any data that may impact analysis\nall_data_cleaned <- all_data_df %>%\n  filter(ride_length > 0) %>%\n  filter(start_station_name !=\"HQ QR\")\nhead(all_data_cleaned)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Descriptive Analysis","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Overall summary of trips \ntrip_stats_summary <- summary(all_data_cleaned$ride_length)\ntrip_stats_summary","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The next section looks at comparing users and members. The code below calculates some of the descriptive statistical values such as the mean, median, max and min values of ride_length by different type of user.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## Calculate mean ride length by group \ntrip_summary_by_group <- all_data_cleaned %>%\n  group_by(member_casual) %>%\n  summarise(mean = mean(ride_length),median = median(ride_length),max = max(ride_length),min = min(ride_length))\ntrip_summary_by_group","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### Having split type by user we now also group by day to see if the day has an impact on the mean value observed.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"### order days of the week \nall_data_cleaned$day_of_week <- ordered(all_data_cleaned$day_of_week, levels=c(\"Sunday\", \"Monday\", \"Tuesday\", \"Wednesday\", \"Thursday\", \"Friday\", \"Saturday\"))\n\n### calculate average ride time by group by day.\nmean_ride_lenght_by_day <- all_data_cleaned %>%\n  group_by(member_casual,day_of_week) %>%\n  summarise(mean = mean(ride_length)) %>%\n  arrange(day_of_week)\n\nmean_ride_lenght_by_day","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### Analyse ridership with data by type and weekday","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#add weekday col to data set \nriders_by_day <- all_data_cleaned %>%\n  mutate(weekday = wday(started_at, label = TRUE)) %>% \n  group_by(member_casual,weekday) %>%\n  summarise(number_of_rides = n(),average_duration = mean(ride_length)) %>%\n  arrange(member_casual,weekday)\n\nriders_by_day","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### The code above sorts riders by group and day. It has several descriptive statistics about the trips and frequency, we will now visualise these relationships ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# visualization of number of rides by rider type\nriders_by_day_viz <- ggplot(data=riders_by_day,aes(x=weekday,y= number_of_rides/1e3, fill = member_casual))+geom_col(position = \"dodge\") + labs(title=\" Number Of Trips\", y= \"Number Of Rides in Thousands\", x=\"Weekday\")\n\nriders_by_day_viz","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"##### we will also visualise the average duration of the journeys ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#visualization of the average duration of rides \n\nduration_of_rides_viz <- ggplot(data=riders_by_day,\n                                aes(x=weekday,y=average_duration,fill = member_casual)) +geom_col(position = \"dodge\") + labs(title=\" Ride Duration By Weekday \", y= \"Average Ride Duration In Seconds\", x=\"Weekday\")\n\nduration_of_rides_viz","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Findings \n##### 1.Casual users on average have lower number of trips for every day of a given week \n##### 2.Casual users on  average 4x ride length \n##### 3.Casual users have higher average trips on weekends where members see lower average usage on weekends\n## Recommendations\n##### 1. Members generate more profit for the company, pricing model likely needs review with ride time as a focus\n##### 2. Marketing campaigns targeting ride duration likely to impact casual users more\n##### 3. Investigate the cause casual user habits ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"## export as csv uncomment\n#write_csv(riders_by_day,\"Cyclistic_riders_data.csv\")\n#write_csv(all_data_cleaned,\"Cyclistic_all_data.csv\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]}]}